ins, Marilyn Strathern, and Arjun Appadurai – have similarly drawn upon particular elements of chaos theory for their inspiration, but as yet there is no focused, comprehensive treatment of the applicability of chaos theory to anthropology’s distinctive ethnographic and cross-cultural materials. This edited volume fills the gap, with both accessible theoretical discussions of chaos theory applications in anthropology and detailed ethnographic and historical illustrations from Africa and Melanesia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aChaotic behavior in systems. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aDamon, Fred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDamon, Frederick H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorava, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMosko, Mark S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMosko, Mark S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPiot, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrathern, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Christopher C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWagner, Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800735187?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800735187423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800735187/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-al